Wick Geometry Channel Project Summary
Overview
This document summarizes the intended channel-detection methodology, the requested logic changes, and the implementation constraints for converting the current TradingView indicator into an outside-in channel finder while preserving the existing script structure.

Core methodology
The preferred geometry starts from the outside in: the true channel rails are defined by extreme pivot trendlines at the structure's outermost boundaries, while the internal distribution of pivots reveals inner rails and determines whether a midpoint is structurally meaningful. The midpoint is therefore a derived line rather than the anchor of the geometry.

The model is explicitly not regression-first. Instead, the preferred slope should come from same-side extreme pivot pairs, and the winning slope should be the one that best aligns with internally derived structure rather than the one that merely accumulates the most weak touches.

A key fractal idea in the model is that an outer rail from an older channel can later become the midpoint of a larger expanded channel. In that interpretation, a widened channel does not replace prior structure so much as reclassify it within a higher-order geometry.

Logic priorities
The preferred hierarchy is:

Outer rails first, derived from extreme pivot pairs.

Internal pivot density second, used to reveal inner rails and validate a midpoint.

Midpoint third, treated as a derived structural line rather than the geometric anchor.

Angle quality over generic containment or arbitrary filtering.

The conceptual scoring model is: the score selects the angle, the chosen outer trendline defines the width, and the equidistant opposite side becomes the predicted rail. This keeps the geometry anchored in price structure rather than in a best-fit regression baseline.

Requested patches
Patch 1
Replace the current regression-first slope selection with slope candidates derived from same-side extreme pivot pairs. The winning slope should be the one with the strongest coherence against the internally derived midpoint, even if an alternative candidate records more weak touches.

This change should avoid arbitrary threshold variables. The underlying price structure should determine which slope is valid.

Patch 2
Any rail with three or more touches should persist as an independent structural trendline, even if it does not win the active channel selection. These confirmed rails should remain on the chart concurrently rather than being discarded as failed channel candidates.

This orphan-rail behavior is compatible with Pine's persistent drawing model, where line objects declared with var can remain active across bars and be updated rather than recreated continuously.

Patch 3
The wider outer rail and its expanded zone should be visually dominant. The widened outer boundary is the most important structural line and should remain clearly visible, with shading preserved to show the expanded width.

Pine supports channel shading between line objects through linefill.new(), which is suitable for emphasizing the expanded zone between two structural rails.

Pine implementation constraints
The requested work was framed as a patch to the existing indicator, not a rewrite. The intended deliverable is a full .pine source file with the current script preserved and the channel-selection logic corrected.

The implementation must avoid undeclared variables, unstable formatting, speculative rewrites, and excessive lookback logic that can trigger max_bars_back errors. Pine's documentation and common troubleshooting guidance both show that uncontrolled series references can produce max_bars_back failures, so bounded pivot logic and disciplined state management are important for robustness.

Because concurrent rails need to persist, array-based or persistent object management may be needed. TradingView documents storing and iterating over line objects so scripts can update existing drawings rather than recreating them each bar.

Visual hierarchy
The outer expanded rail should be the strongest visual object because it represents the extreme structural boundary. Orphan rails with three or more touches should remain visible as valid structure, but they should stay visually secondary to the active outer channel.

This hierarchy is logical within Pine's line-and-fill model: the dominant boundary can be reinforced with stronger color and fill opacity, while secondary persistent rails can remain thinner or less opaque without losing structural meaning.

Conversation outcome
The conceptual goal became clearer over the course of the discussion even though delivery failed. The final position was consistent: outer extremes define the true rails, internal pivot density defines inner rails and the midpoint, the midpoint is derived rather than primary, and confirmed three-touch rails remain valid structure even when they do not win active channel selection.

The main failure point was delivery and file access rather than methodology. The requested next-step artifact, if work resumes, should be a complete patched Pine file implementing pivot-derived slope selection, persistent orphan rails, and visually prominent widened outer-channel shading.

