so how to accomplish my goal of finding the best fit channel from the outside-in, looking for pairs of parallel trendlines, using price clusters to estimate the slope and validate trendlines?

You accomplish it by treating channel-finding as a voting/search problem over angle families, not as a fitted line problem. The right primitive is: generate candidate slopes from outer wick pairs, cluster near-identical slopes, then validate each slope by checking whether parallel rails and internal lines attract repeated wick acknowledgments from both sides.

Core method
Start from the outside in:

Pick anchor candidates

Use your P1 rules first: manual anchor or session-defined significant highs/lows, especially Asia/London reversals.

Build candidate same-side outer rails from meaningful wick pairs, not from all bars equally.

Estimate slope from wick pairs

For each same-side wick pair, compute slope.

Bin similar slopes together so near-identical angles vote as one Гўв‚¬Е“angle familyГўв‚¬Вќ instead of fragmenting into tiny differences. That is the Hough-style part: wick points vote into angle bins.

Validate slope with price clusters

For each slope family, project candidate lines through wick clusters and count how many highs or lows fall within tolerance of those parallels.

Favor slopes that produce repeated clusters on both sides of the eventual midline, not just one lucky outer rail.

Build the channel
Once a slope family survives, build the channel using the TradingView-style primitive you described: 2-point slope + 1-point parallel offset. In other words, points 1 and 2 lock the angle, and point 3 can be in the past and simply defines the parallel offset that sets width.

Then test all same-side wick pairs for valid parallel rails at that slope, because wick 1 and wick 3 may be the real rail even if wick 1 and 2 are not. Among matching parallels, keep the nearest meaningful rejection line and reject looser outer envelopes if a tighter inner rail explains the structure better.

Score the candidate
The score should be dominated by geometry, not enclosure:

Highest weight: expanded high/low pivot touches and parallel cluster quality.

Next: two-sided midline or internal-line touches at 25/50/75 or other tested fractions.

Next: symmetry of deviations around the midline and alternation quality of peaks/troughs.

Lower weight: rail rebounds and body containment.

That matches your stated goal that the correct angle matters more than late outer rebounds, and that width should come from geometry around the slope rather than from generic containment.

Practical Pine version
In Pine, the workable implementation is:

Restrict the working window to the P1-defined session span or nearby relevant lookback.

Use selected wick points or pivots, not every OHLC point, to keep computation manageable.

Quantize slope into coarse bins first, then refine around the winning bin.

For the best slope family, test parallel offsets from opposite-side wick clusters and score each candidate channel family.

Persist a best channel and a new/potential channel as state objects candle by candle, instead of redrawing from scratch each time.

So the short answer is: donГўв‚¬в„ўt search for a line; search for a slope family supported by wick clusters, then search for the best pair of parallel rails at that slope. That is the outside-in method closest to how you already draw channels manually.


